The paper presents a novel class of robots with non-holonomic constraints and closed-loop kinematic chains, and describes a trajectory optimization method that is general with respect to the number of robots, topology of the kinematic chains, and placement of actuators. These characteristics suggest that the paper is likely to belong to the Robotics (cs.RO) sub-category. Additionally, the paper discusses the optimization of design parameters and control policies, which could fall under the Systems and Control (cs.SY) sub-category. The paper also mentions examples of CCMA systems and their simulation results, which could be relevant to the Multi-Agent Systems (cs.MA) sub-category. The use of optimization methods for tasks such as internal collision avoidance and external obstacle avoidance could be related to the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category. Finally, the validation of the trajectory optimization method through experiments could be relevant to the Learning (cs.LG) sub-category.
